    "Therefore, from the triangle inequality and Lemma 5.2 we have| Q i f i det Dπ i - Q i g i det Dκ i | ≤ i | Q f i det Dπ i - Q g i det Dκ i | ≤ r d+1 1 2 √ d i (Lip(f i) + Lip(g i))L d i + r d i |(f i) Q -(g i) Q |L d i + r d-1 c d i |(f i) Q |L d-1 i ∥π i -κ i ∥ ℓ ∞ (∂Q).",
    "(5.10)Writing L d-1 as L d 2 L d 2 -1 and using Holder's inequality yields i |(f i) Q |L d-1 i ∥π i -κ i ∥ ℓ ∞ (∂Q) ≤ sup i {|(f i) Q |} i L d 2 (L d 2 -1 ∥π i -κ i ∥ ℓ ∞ (∂Q)) ≤ sup i {|(f i) Q |} i L d i i L d-2 i ∥π i -κ i ∥ 2 ℓ ∞ (∂Q).The last estimate combined with (5.10) yields the desired inequality (5.9).Note that even if it assumed that i (f i, π i) and i (g i, κ i) are formal Lipschitz sums, it is still possible that the right hand side of the estimate (5.9) is infinite.",
    "This may for example happen if L i is much larger than  d j=1 Lip(π j i)   1 d.To avoid this issue (which is really only of technical nature) we shall consider sums where L i is the correct number to use.",
    "Definition 5.4.",
    "A formal Lipschitz sumi (f i, κ i) is called regular if (i) for each i either f i = π i = 0 or max{Lip(f i), ∥f i ∥ ∞ } = 1 and Lip(π j i) = Lip(π k i) for all j, k ∈ {1,..., d}, (ii) for each i ∈ N, π i (0) = 0.If the regular formal Lipschitz sum with which we are working is clear from context, the symbol L i stands for the value Lip(π j i) where j ∈ {1,..., d} is arbitrary.Proposition 5.5."
